article.description: Ketia Swanier scored a career-high 20 points, leading top-ranked Connecticut to a 98-41 rout Saturday of St. John's, which suspended six players just before the game.

related.description: St. John's coach Kim Barnes has suspended six players ahead of the game against No. 1 Connecticut.
related.linkText: St. John's suspends six before game vs. UConn
related.title: Six Red Storm players suspended for violating unspecified team policy
related.headline: Six Red Storm players suspended for violating unspecified team policy

article.headline: St. John's roughed up by Swanier, UConn after suspending six
article.linkText: Top-ranked UConn routs short-handed St. John's
article.story:
STORRS, Conn. -- Connecticut guard Ketia Swanier's credentials for the Big East Conference's sixth-man award may be in jeopardy.

The senior started her second consecutive game and scored a career-high 20 points Saturday, leading the top-ranked Huskies to a 98-41 rout of St. John's.

UConn coach Geno Auriemma said he's been notified by the conference that if Swanier starts twice more this season, she'll be declared ineligible for the award that honors the conference's top reserve.

"I'm going to have to take that into consideration, because I'd hate for her to lose something that I think she deserves," Auriemma said.

Swanier, one of four seniors honored before their final on-campus game, hit 6-of-9 3-pointers and had five assists and four steals. She moved into the starting lineup on Wednesday against Marquette, after spending most of the season as Connecticut's first player off the bench.

"Pretty much for most of the season my shot has felt like that, and today it was just falling and it felt extra nice," she said.

St. John's, already a big underdog, suspended six players before the game. Kia Wright, Nikki Jo Rotolo, Charisse Curtis, Kristin Moore, Sheree Ledbetter and Recee Mitchell violated a team policy, coach Kim Barnes Arico said.

"They didn't do anything terrible," she said. "There's no drinking, drugs or anything like that. They just made a poor decision that I was really unhappy with."

The Red Storm's remaining six players each played at least 27 minutes.

Kelly McManmon led the Red Storm (13-13, 4-9) with 15. Monique McLean, who came in averaging just under 20 points a game, was held to just six points on 2-of-15 shooting. She needed just seven points to become the 16th St. John's player to reach 1,000 points.

Renee Montgomery and Maya Moore each added 18 for UConn (26-1, 13-1 Big East), which remained a half-game ahead of Rutgers for first place in the conference. The two teams play each other in the regular-season finale March 3.

Moore also had 11 rebounds, giving the freshman seven double-doubles. 13-12.

St. John's stayed with the Huskies early. Tiina Sten had six points and 5 minutes into the game UConn led by just one, 13-12.

Connecticut, led by Swanier, then went on an 11-0 run. She took six shots in the half, all from behind the arc, and hit five of them.

UConn went to press with just over 3 minutes left in the half and built the lead to 52-27 at the break.

The Huskies opened the second half on an 8-0 run, capped by a fast-break layup from Swanier, her first basket from inside the arc.

A Maya Moore 3-pointer capped a 13-0 run that made it 75-36.

The Huskies scored more than 90 points for the third consecutive game, and held St. John's to just 14 second-half points.

"We're able to get a lot of easy baskets," Auriemma said. "Usually when you score a lot of points, that is what you are getting, you're getting a lot of 3s, you're getting a lot of easy baskets."

Connecticut honored seniors Swanier, Houston, Brittany Hunter and Mel Thomas, before the game. UConn has a 115-18 record during their four years, have won two conference tournament titles, and have advanced to the NCAA Regional finals twice, but have not made it to the Final Four.

Only Houston and Swanier played. Thomas suffered a season-ending knee injury in January and Hunter was sidelined with soreness in her surgically repaired right knee.

Houston, making her sixth start of the year, scored 12 points and pulled down seven rebounds.

"We wanted to make sure we came out as a team and [did] exactly what we're supposed to do," Houston said. "Because this would be a terrible day to win a game, but not play as well and walk around thinking we lost."

Connecticut next travels to Baton Rouge and a date with No. 6 LSU, the team that beat the Huskies in last year's Fresno Regional final, 73-50.

At the start of this season, UConn center Tina Charles put up a photo in her locker of LSU's Sylvia Fowles blocking one of her shots.

"That's just a thing of motivation," Charles said. "It's actually a picture from that game and the feeling that I had after that game that I don't want to experience."
